# Git Commands for Daily Workflow

These commands are used when you make daily changes to your code, fix bugs, or want to view older versions of your project.

## 1. Code Tracking and Verification

| Command | Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| **`git diff`** | Shows line-by-line changes made to files that are not yet staged. |
| **`git log`** | Displays the complete commit history of the repository. |
| **`git log --oneline`** | Shows the commit history in a condensed, clean, one-line format. |

## 2. Branching (Testing new features without affecting the main code)

| Command | Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| **`git branch`** | Lists all the branches in your current repository. |
| **`git checkout -b <branch_name>`** | Creates a new branch and immediately switches to it. |
| **`git checkout <branch_name>`** | Switches from your current branch to another existing branch. |
| **`git merge <branch_name>`** | Merges the code of the specified branch into your current active branch (e.g., `main`). |
| **`git branch -d <branch_name>`** | Deletes a local branch after its work has been completed and merged. |

## 3. Syncing with Remote Repository (GitHub)

| Command | Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| **`git fetch`** | Downloads information about new changes from GitHub without modifying or overwriting your local code. |
| **`git pull`** | Downloads the latest code from GitHub and immediately merges (updates) it into your local code. |
